Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c\n@@ -3257,8 +3257,13 @@\n     if (initialised) {\n-        wrefresh(stdscr);\n-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n+        if (stdscr == NULL) {\n+            initialised = FALSE;\n+            PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, "curses not properly initialized: stdscr is NULL");\n+            return NULL;\n+        }\n+        wrefresh(stdscr);\n+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);\n     }\n \n     win = initscr();\n \n-    if (win == NULL) {\n-        PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);\n-        return NULL;\n-    }\n+    if (win == NULL || stdscr == NULL) {\n+        initialised = FALSE;\n+        PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);\n+        return NULL;\n+    }\n \n     initialised = initialised_setupterm = TRUE;\n'}`
responded: The repeated sanitizer report and validation failures indicate that the root cause is that `initialised` can be set to true even if `stdscr` is later destroyed or invalid, and the code does not reinitialize or check `stdscr` in the fast path (`if (initialised) ...`). This means that after a failed or partial initialization, or after curses teardown, `initialised` remains true but `stdscr` is not valid, causing the crash.

**Robust Fix:**
- In the `if (initialised)` block, always check that `stdscr` is non-NULL before using it.
- In the slow path, after `initscr()`, check both `win` and `stdscr` before setting `initialised`.
- If either is NULL, do not set `initialised`.

**Patch:**
```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -3257,8 +3257,13 @@
     if (initialised) {
-        wrefresh(stdscr);
-        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
+        if (stdscr == NULL) {
+            initialised = FALSE;
+            PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, "curses not properly initialized: stdscr is NULL");
+            return NULL;
+        }
+        wrefresh(stdscr);
+        return (PyObject *)PyCursesWindow_New(stdscr, NULL);
     }

     win = initscr();

-    if (win == NULL) {
-        PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);
-        return NULL;
-    }
+    if (win == NULL || stdscr == NULL) {
+        initialised = FALSE;
+        PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);
+        return NULL;
+    }

     initialised = initialised_setupterm = TRUE;
```
This ensures that `initialised` is only true when `stdscr` is valid, and disables the fast path if `stdscr` is not valid.

I will now validate this patch.

